§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Given $a, b, c$ nonzero real numbers, find $x$ to solve
    $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$. ⦉
⦉

§ Result ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ Let $a, b, c ∈ 𝗥$ nonzero. ⦉

  ‖ Then both
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} ⦉

      ‖ \quad \text{ and } \quad ⦉

      ‖ \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} ⦉
    ⦉
    are solutions of
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ ax^2 + bx + c = 0. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
</statement>
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We call $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$ a ❬quadratic equation❭.
    † ⦊
      ‖ Future editions will prove via completing the square. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ The solutions are often writen in short hand
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}, ⦉
    ⦉
    which is called the ❬quadratic formula❭. ⦉
⦉

§ Proof ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ Let $p, q ∈ 𝗥$ be real numbers. ⦉

  ‖ Suppose $x ∈ 𝗥$ satisfies the second-degree equation
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x^2 + px + q = 0 ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Then
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x ∈ \set{-\frac{p}{2} + \sqrt{\frac{p^2}{4} - q},
        -\frac{p}{2} - \sqrt{\frac{p^2}{4} - q}} ⦉
    ⦉⦉
</statement>
<proof>
  ‖ Suppose $x ∈ 𝗥$ satisfies
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x^2 + px + q = 0 ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ This holds if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x^2 + px = -q ⦉
    ⦉
    which holds if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x^2 + px + \frac{p^2}{4} = \frac{p^2}{4} - q ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ We can express the left hand side as
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x^2 + px + \frac{p^2}{4} = \left(x + \frac{p}{2}\right)^2 ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ By substituting this into the left hand side, we have that
    $x$ is a solution if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \left(x + \frac{p}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{p^2}{4} - q, ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Hence $x$ is a solution if and only if $x + p/2$ is a
    square root of $p^2/4 - q$. ⦉

  ‖ As usual, there are two quantities, which we denote as
    usual with $\sqrt{·}$, so that $x$ is a solution if and
    only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x + \frac{p}{2} = ±\sqrt{\frac{p^2}{4} - q} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Consequently, $x$ is a solution if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x = -\frac{p}{2} ± \sqrt{\frac{p^2}{4} - q} ⦉
    ⦉⦉
</proof>
<statement type='corollary'>
  ‖ A real number $x$ satisfies $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$ if and
    only if $x = \frac{-b ± \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}$. ⦉
</statement>
<proof>
  ‖ Divide through by $a$. ⦉

  ‖ Define $p = b/a$ and $q = c/a$. ⦉

  ‖ Then we have that $x$ is a solution if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x = -\frac{b}{2a} ± \sqrt{\frac{b^2}{4a^2} - \frac{c}{a}} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Which holds if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x = \frac{-b}{2a} ± \sqrt{\frac{b^2}{4a^2} -
        \frac{4ac}{4a^2}} ⦉
    ⦉
    which holds if and only if
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ x = \frac{-b ± \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}, ⦉
    ⦉
    as desired. ⦉
</proof>
